'''Christian Kern''' (<small>Austrian</small> {{IPA-de|ˈkrɪstja:n ˈkɛrn}}; born 4 January 1966) was [[Chancellor of Austria]] from 17 May 2016 to 18 December 2017 and [[Chairperson of the Social Democratic Party of Austria|chairman of the]] [[Social Democratic Party of Austria|Social Democratic Party]] from 25 June 2016 to 25 September 2018.

A business journalist by profession, the member of Austria's Social Democratic Party served as spokesman of the SPÖ's parliamentary group leader in the mid-1990s, before he became a senior manager in Austria's leading electricity company [[Verbund|Verbund AG]]. In 2010, Kern was appointed [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of the state-owned [[Austrian Federal Railways]] (ÖBB), chairing the [[Community of European Railway and Infrastructure Companies]] (CER) from 2014 onwards. Following the resignation of [[Werner Faymann]] amidst the [[Austrian presidential election, 2016|presidential election]], the governing Social Democrats nominated Kern for the office of Chancellor.

Kern was sworn in as Chancellor of Austria on 17 May 2016, vowing to continue the "[[Grand coalition#Austria|Grand coalition]]" with the [[Austrian People's Party|People's Party]] (ÖVP), but promising a "[[New Deal]]" that would bring about more jobs by cutting [[red tape]] while ensuring ordinary workers receive a share of economic prosperity. Kern criticized the Austrian political elite as being power-obsessed and devoid of a meaningful political agenda about the country's future.

== Early life and education ==
Kern was raised in [[Simmering (Vienna)|Simmering]], a working-class district of Vienna, as the son of an electrician and a secretary.<ref name=TheLocal>{{cite news |title=Christian Kern: no more normal service |publisher=[[The Local]] |url=http://www.thelocal.at/20160513/christian-kern-no-more-normal-service |date=13 May 2016 |accessdate=23 May 2016}}</ref> He studied [[journalism]] and [[communication studies|communication]] at the [[University of Vienna]] followed by postgraduate education at the Management Zentrum St. Gallen.

== Career ==
Kern started his career in 1989 as a [[Business journalism|business journalist]] writing for the ''Wirtschaftspressedienst'' and Austrian business magazine ''Option''. In 1991, he became an assistant of the [[Federal Chancellery of Austria|Federal Chancellery]]'s undersecretary of state for civil service, {{Interlanguage link multi|Peter Kostelka|de}}. When Kostelka became chairman of the [[Social Democratic Party of Austria|Social Democratic Party]] (SPÖ) parliamentary group in 1994, Kern remained his chief of office and spokesman.

In 1997, Kern moved to the largest Austrian electricity supplier, the [[Verbund AG]], where from 1999 he oversaw marketing and sales. In 2007 he was appointed a senior manager overseeing foreign [[mergers & acquisitions]], investments, and the Austrian [[Electric power transmission|high-voltage transmission grid]]<ref name=derstandard/>

===CEO of the Austrian Federal Railways===
[[File:Christian Kern Eröffnung BahnhofCity Wien West 2011 a.jpg|thumb|Kern 2011 at the opening of the modernized ''[[Wien Westbahnhof railway station|Bahnhofscity Wien West]]'']]
[[File:20120425 1035 Semmeringbasistunnel Spatenstich 0590.jpg|thumb|Kern with Transport Minister [[Doris Bures]] at the ground-breaking ceremony of the {{Interlanguage link multi|Semmering-Basistunnel|de}}]]

In 2010, Kern was selected to take over the post as CEO of the [[Austrian Federal Railways]] (ÖBB).<ref name=TheLocal /> He was appointed chairman of the [[Community of European Railway and Infrastructure Companies]] (CER) in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=CER Chairman Christian Kern to become new Austrian Chancellor {{!}} CER:Home|url=http://www.cer.be/media/press-releases/cer-chairman-christian-kern-become-new-austrian-chancellor|publisher=[[Community of European Railway and Infrastructure Companies]]|accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> Kern has been a board member of [[FK Austria Wien]] since 2009.

In 2012, ÖBB celebrated the 175th anniversary of the ''[[North railway (Austria)|Nordbahn]]'', the earliest predecessor company marking the start of [[rail transport in Austria]]. Kern inaugurated an exhibition on the company's complicity with the [[Third Reich]], named "The Suppressed Years – Railway and National Socialism in Austria 1938–1945". He referred to that period as "the darkest part of our company's history," adding that "We are obliged to commemorate and with this documentation we would like to further contribute to coming to terms with the past. No matter how incredible these events may seem to us today, we need to clearly accept these times as part of our ÖBB history."<ref>{{cite press release |title="Repressed Years – the Austrian Railways and National Socialism between 1938 and 1945" |publisher=Agentur Milli Segal |url=http://www.millisegal.at/obb/index.php/presse/presse-engl |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611101003/http://www.millisegal.at/obb/index.php/presse/presse-engl |archive-date=11 June 2015 |dead-url=no}}</ref> The exhibition later went on tour and was presented at the [[European Parliament]]'s [[Espace Léopold|parliamentary building in Brussels]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Suppressed Years Railway and National Socialism in Austria 1938 – 1945 |publisher=[[Austrian Federal Railways|ÖBB]] |url=http://konzern.oebb.at/de/verdraengtejahre/Infoflyer_Exhibition_The_Suppressed_Years.pdf |year=2014 |accessdate=21 May 2016 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> For his extraordinary engagement accounting for the company's past, in June 2013 the [[Israelitische Kultusgemeinde Wien|Vienna Israelite Community]] awarded Kern the [[Marietta and Friedrich Torberg Medal]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Torberg-Medaille für Christian Kern |publisher=ÖBB |url=http://konzern.oebb.at/de/verdraengtejahre/Torberg-Medaille/index.jsp |accessdate=21 May 2016 |language=de |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512190658/http://konzern.oebb.at/de/verdraengtejahre/Torberg-Medaille/index.jsp |archivedate=12 May 2016 |df= }}</ref>

In the course of the 2015 [[European migrant crisis|migrant crisis]], Kern organized the transport of hundred thousands of migrants coming from the "[[Balkan route]]" across the country. He is considered a supporter of German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]]'s migration policy.<ref name=FT0517>{{cite news |author=Ralph Atkins |title=New Austrian leader warns mainstream parties may ‘disappear’ |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5333d224-1c33-11e6-b286-cddde55ca122.html |date=17 May 2016 |accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> Leading [[Austrian Trade Union Federation|Austrian trade unionist]] {{Interlanguage link multi|Roman Hebenstreit|de}}, who is also chairman of the ÖBB's [[works council]] described Kern in 2016 as "the first ÖBB boss to really stand by his workers."<ref name=TheLocal />

===Chancellor of Austria===
[[File:Angelobung Minister 180516-11 (27022502891) (2).jpg|thumb|Kern with outgoing President [[Heinz Fischer]] and Vice Chancellor [[Reinhold Mitterlehner]] at the swearing-in ceremony of his new cabinet members on 18 May 2016]]
[[File:2016 Alexander Van der Bellen Christian Kern (31391029670).jpg|thumb|Kern with Austrian President [[Alexander Van der Bellen]], 20 December 2016]]
{{see also|Kern government}}
Since 2014, Kern was repeatedly named as one of the possible successors for [[Werner Faymann]]'s Chancellor post.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Rosemarie Schwaiger |title=ÖBB-Chef Christian Kern hat Chancen, Nachfolger von Kanzler Faymann zu werden |magazine=[[Profil (magazine)|profil]]|url=http://www.profil.at/oesterreich/oebb-chef-christian-kern-chancen-nachfolger-kanzler-faymann-377137 |date=2 August 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref> In 2015, Austrian news magazine ''[[Profil (magazine)|profil]]'' referred to him as the "Chancellor of hearts" and the Federal Railways he led as "the only state institution that flawlessly worked amidst the refugee crisis."<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Eva Linsinger |title=Christian Kern: Kanzler der Herzen |magazine=[[Profil (magazine)|profil]] |url=http://www.profil.at/oesterreich/christian-kern-kanzler-der-herzen-5858210 |date=16 September 2015 |accessdate=21 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref>

Half a year later, when on 9 May 2016 Chancellor Faymann resigned from all his posts, Kern was again named one of the candidates alongside Time Warner manager [[Gerhard Zeiler]] and former Siemens manager {{Interlanguage link multi|Brigitte Ederer|de}}.<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Eric Frey]] |title=Kanzlernachfolge: Lieber Zeiler als Kern |newspaper=[[Der Standard]] |url=http://derstandard.at/2000036615981/Kanzlernachfolge-Lieber-Zeiler-als-Kern |date=11 May 2016 |accessdate=21 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref> On a 12 May party session, the Social Democrats agreed on nominating Kern for the country's highest executive office. He was announced to be appointed the new Chancellor by 17 May, and to be nominated as party chairman at the upcoming party congress on 25 June.<ref>{{cite web |title=SPÖ legt sich offenbar fest |publisher=[[ORF (broadcaster)|ORF]] |url=http://orf.at/stories/2339106/ |date=12 May 2016 |accessdate=12 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Cynthia Kroet |title=Christian Kern named as new Austrian Chancellor |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/christian-kern-named-as-new-austrian-chancellor/ |work=[[Politico]] |date=12 May 2016 |accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> Kern was sworn into office on 17 May by outgoing President [[Heinz Fischer]].

At his first press conference, Kern called for a change in the style of cooperation within the coalition government, warning the two parties risked otherwise "disappearing from the screen". He reaffirmed his position that in the refugee crisis, Austria was right not to "leave women and children standing in the rain," while ensuring order and security.<ref name=FT0517 />

In spite of his credentials as a manager, Kern's nomination of members of the party's left wing, {{Interlanguage link multi|Sonja Wehsely|de}} and [[Jörg Leichtfried]] as new ministers was interpreted as a turn towards the party's left.<ref>{{cite news |author=Oliver Pink |title=Christian Kern: Ein Pragmatiker mit Linksdrall |newspaper=[[Die Presse]] |url=http://diepresse.com/home/politik/innenpolitik/4987560/Christian-Kern_Ein-Pragmatiker-mit-Linksdrall |date=12 May 2016 |accessdate=21 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref> The appointment of Wehsely, who is known for her staunch pro-asylum course during the [[European migrant crisis]], was however considered all too controversial, with political analyst Thomas Hofer referring to it as a declaration of war (''"kleine Kampfansage"'') against conservative coalition partner [[Austrian People's Party|ÖVP]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Wehsely als Ministerin wäre "Kampfansage" |publisher=[[ORF (broadcaster)|ORF]] |url=http://wien.orf.at/news/stories/2774116/ |date=13 May 2016 |accessdate=21 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref> Wehsely ultimately declined and decided she would stay city councillor in Vienna.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wehsely sagt Kern ab |newspaper=[[Österreich (newspaper)|Österreich]] |url=http://www.oe24.at/oesterreich/politik/Wehsely-sagt-Kern-ab/235879569 |date=16 May 2016 |accessdate=21 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref> Hofer however expects Kern to follow the centrist examples of German chancellor [[Gerhard Schröder]] or Britain's [[Tony Blair]], combining pro-business policies with a social conscience.<ref name=TheLocal />

Kern appointed [[Muna Duzdar]], a lawyer and chairwoman of the Palestininian-Austrian Society, as state secretary in the Chancellery, where she will be the first Muslim to hold a government post.<ref>{{cite news |title=Muna Duzdar: Faymann-Kritikerin sitzt nun im Kanzleramt |newspaper=[[Die Presse]] |url=http://diepresse.com/home/politik/innenpolitik/4990042/Duzdar_FaymannKritikerin-sitzt-nun-im-Kanzleramt |date=17 May 2016 |accessdate=27 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref> The fact that Duzdar, who has previously come out as a sharp critic of Israel, will now be in charge of Jewish community affairs, irritated the Jewish community. According to ''[[Jerusalem Post]]'' author Samuel Laster, Duzdar's appointment may however be considered a "signal of openness" for Kern who is "widely regarded as a friend of Israel."<ref>{{cite news |author=Samuel Laster |title=Austria’s election, Jews and Israel |newspaper=[[Jerusalem Post]] |url=http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Austrias-election-Jews-and-Israel-454925 |date=24 May 2016 |accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>

Soon after taking office, Kern's government implemented several law-and-order measures, including a ban on Muslim face-covering veils and a tightening of immigration rules.<ref>Shadia Nasralla and Francois Murphy (April 6, 2017), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-austria-politics-alliance-idUSKBN1781P9 Austrian Social Democrats move toward ending ban on far-right alliances] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref>

In June 2017, Kern criticized the draft of new U.S. sanctions against [[Russia]] that target EU–Russia energy projects, including [[Nord Stream|Nord Stream 2]] gas pipeline.<ref>"[http://www.politico.eu/article/germany-and-austria-warn-u-s-over-expanded-russia-sanctions/ Germany and Austria warn US over expanded Russia sanctions]". ''[[Politico]]''. June 15, 2017.</ref> In a joint statement Kern and [[Germany]]'s foreign minister [[Sigmar Gabriel]] said that "Europe's energy supply is a matter for Europe, and not for the United States of America."<ref>"[https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2017-06-15/germany-austria-slam-us-sanctions-against-russia Germany, Austria Slam US Sanctions Against Russia]". U.S. News. June 15, 2017.</ref> 

===Campaign for the 2019 European elections===
In September 2018, Kern announced that he would resign as national party leader and instead run as top candidate for the Austrian Social Democrats in the [[European Parliament election, 2019|European Parliament elections]].<ref>Kirsti Knolle (September 18, 2018), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-austria-politics-opposition/austrian-center-left-ex-chancellor-kern-to-run-for-european-parliament-idUSKCN1LY2YA Austrian center-left ex-chancellor Kern to run for European Parliament] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref>

==Other activities==
* [[FK Austria Wien]], Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[http://www.fk-austria.at/de/klub/verein/ Board of Trustees] [[FK Austria Wien]].</ref>
* [[Konzerthaus, Vienna|Konzerthaus Vienna]], Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://konzerthaus.at/kuratorium Board of Trustees] [[Konzerthaus, Vienna|Konzerthaus Vienna]].</ref>
* Rechtskomitee LAMBDA (RKL), Member of the Board of Trustees
* Business Forum of the Social Democratic Party of Germany, Member of the Political Advisory Board (since 2018)<ref>[https://www.spd-wirtschaftsforum.de/presse/bernd-westphal-wird-neuer-beirats-vorsitzender-beim-wirtschaftsforum-der-spd/ Bernd Westphal wird neuer Beirats-Vorsitzender beim Wirtschaftsforum der SPD] Business Forum of the Social Democratic Party of Germany , press release of June 7, 2018.</ref>

== Personal life ==
In 1985 Kern married Karin Wessely, with whom he has three sons. In 2001, his marriage with Wessely, who is a local SPÖ politician in [[Mödling]], a district capital south of Vienna, ended in divorce. Wessely however supported his nomination as successor to Faymann, and highly praised him as a charismatic personality, who is able to unite the more left-aligned and the more right-aligned factions of their party.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-Frau hofft auf Christian Kern |url=http://www.noen.at/nachrichten/lokales/aktuell/moedling/Ex-Frau-hofft-auf-Christian-Kern;art2664,737274 |newspaper=[[Niederösterreichische Nachrichten]] |date=11 May 2016 |accessdate=12 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref> With his second wife, Eveline Steinberger, he has a daughter.<ref name=derstandard>{{cite news |author=Luise Ungerboeck |title=Kopf des Tages: Christian Kern |url=http://derstandard.at/1267743631579/Kopf-des-Tages-Christian-Kern |newspaper=[[Der Standard]] |date=10 March 2010 |accessdate=11 May 2016 |language=de}}</ref>

