[[Image:NY John Jovino Firearms - panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Sign]] [[File:John Jovino gun shop 183 Grand St sunny morn jeh.JPG|thumb|Shop]] '''John Jovino Gun Shop''' or the '''John Jovino Company''' is a firearms dealer and factory located at [[Grand Street (Manhattan)|183 Grand Street]], in [[Little Italy, Manhattan|Little Italy]], a neighborhood of the [[New York City]] borough of [[Manhattan]]. It is the oldest gun retailer in New York City<ref name="Newman">{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D06E7D6173AF93BA25757C0A9659C8B63 |title=New York Dealers Are Prominent on Court Case's List of Guns Tied to Crime |author=Andy Newman |date=April 18, 2003 |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=2007-11-09}}</ref> and said to be the oldest gun shop in the United States.<ref name="Weinstein">{{cite news |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0743,weinstein,78160,6.html |title=Chinatown mystery: Why did officials from the bloodiest country on earth stock up at a local gun shop? |author=Adam Weinstein |date=October 23, 2007 |publisher=Village Voice |accessdate=2007-11-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026104518/http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0743%2Cweinstein%2C78160%2C6.html |archivedate=October 26, 2007 |df= }}</ref>
The store, which is known for its sign depicting a revolver, was founded in 1911 by John Jovino who sold it to the Imperato family in the 1920s.<ref name="Weinstein"/>{{dead link|date=December 2016}} It remains in the family.<ref name="Newman"/> The store was once located at 5 [[Centre Market Place]], part of a gun district behind the former [[240 Centre Street|police headquarters]] on [[Centre Street (Manhattan)|Centre Street]], but later moved to its present location.
The store "does about $1 million worth of business annually", a figure which was higher before the [[New York Police Department]] opened an internal firearms bureau.<ref name="Weinstein"/>{{dead link|date=December 2016}} The company used to own a gun factory in [[Brooklyn]], the only one in the city, which made [[Colt M1911]] pistols and reproductions of [[American Civil War]]-era [[Henry rifle]]s.<ref name="Kennedy">{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DE0DE143FF936A35757C0A9669C8B63 |title=PUBLIC LIVES; Selling Guns: A Tradition and a Dilemma |author=Randy Kennedy |date=April 5, 2000 |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=2007-11-09}}</ref> The company, known as [[Henry Repeating Arms]], moved its headquarters from New York City to [[Bayonne, New Jersey]], in 2013.
Although many of its customers are in law enforcement, the company was near the top of a list of sellers whose guns were linked to New York City crimes in a 2003 report by a [[Columbia University]] researcher using data from the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms]]. Some 102 guns of 11,700 used in crimes and later identified came from the Jovino shop.<ref name="Newman"/> According to current owners, until the 1980s the Jovino Company was "one of the biggest dealers in the country" and sold guns to many police departments. The study did not suggest any wrongdoing by the dealers listed (the store is not responsible for how people use the products they legally sell) and did not take into account that a store that has a higher volume of sales would most likely have a higher number of sales to people who later used the firearms in crimes, even if the store had a lower ratio of firearms used in crimes bought from the store per total sales than a store with a smaller volume of sales.<ref name="Newman"/> A 2007 ''[[Village Voice]]'' article raised questions about the store's sales to [[United Nations]] diplomats from the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]].<ref name="Weinstein"/>{{dead link|date=December 2016}}
The shop was seen in the film ''[[Serpico]]'', in the thirteenth episode (Season One) of ''Law and Order (A Death in the Family)'' and very briefly in ''[[Mean Streets]]'' as well as ''[[The Brave One (2007 film)|The Brave One]]''. The shop’s Centre Market Street location was seen in the 1957 television series ''[[Decoy]]'', appearing in the first season, episode four, titled ''[[To Trap a Thief]]''.
